OBSERVATION.
—
Sergeant
C.,
223rd
infantry,
was
sent

to
us
on
August
29th
1918
from
the
Val
de
Grace
hospital

for
physiotherapy.
He
showed
a
dropping
of
the
stump
of
the

left
shoulder
and
scar
tissue
in
the
cervico-dorsal
region
of
the

back
due
to
shell
wounds.
On
further
examination
we
noted

a
badly
consolidated
fracture
of
the
lower
jaw
and
a
salivary

fistula
below
Stenon's
duct.

C.
gave
a
history
of
having
been
wounded
on
June
3rd
1918

and
admitted
to
Val-de-Grace,
where
a
curettage
of
the
maxil-

lary
fracture
was
performed
on
the
5th.
The
wound
continued

to
suppurate,
however,
and
a
bone
splinter
was
subsequently

removed
by
operation.
Nevertheless
the
suppuration
took

more
than
a
month
to
disappear;
and
when
it
did
so
patient

became
aware
that
the
scar
was
continuously
wet
with
saliva,

which
exuded
freely,
especially
after
mastication.
Every
now

and
then,
or
on
any
effort
to
cough
or
breathe
heavily,
patient

noticed
that
food
particles
which
had
remained
in
the
mouth

ran
out
from
the
passage
with
the
saliva.

When
patient
presented
himself
at
the
physiotherapeutical

service
he
was
carrying
a
compress
in
his
hand
for
mopping

up
the
saliva,
which
was
so
abundant
that
he
had
to
make

several
lavages
per
day
with
permanganate
of
potash.
The

mobile
fragment
of
the
fractured
jaw
promoted
salivation,
and

had
produced
an
inflamed
condition
of
the
cicatrix.
Moreover,

the
face
showed
infiltration
of
the
cheek
and
a
pronounced

congestion
of
the
scar
tissue.
Patient
was
badly
nourished,

masticated
with
difficulty,
and
was
at
the
same
time
suffering

from
a
partial
constriction
of
the
jaw
(18
m/m).
His
general

condition
was
unsatisfactory,
and
he
showed
an
inclination
to

abstain
from
all
effort
as
far
as
possible
in
order
not
to
increase

the
flow
of
saliva.

We
began
our
treatment
of
the
fistula
first
of
all
with
gentle

massage,
—
superficial
effleurages
from
the
periphery
of
the

infiltrated
mass
towards
the
cicatrix,
followed
by
light
pressure
